05586nam a22008175i 9780812205930DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20112011pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013938007  a(OCoLC)1029812621  a(OCoLC)979910400  a97808122059307 a10.9783/97808122059302doi  a(DE-B1597)449426  a(OCoLC)794700590  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aHIS0360302bisacsh04a138.0973090341 aLukasik, Christopher J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDiscerning Characters :bThe Culture of Appearance in Early America /cChristopher J. Lukasik. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (328 p.) :b28 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEarly American Studies00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tPART I. Distinction and the Face -- tChapter 1. Discerning Characters -- tChapter 2. Reading and Breeding -- tChapter 3. Th e Face of Seduction -- tChapter 4. The Face of the Public -- tPART II. The Changing Face of the Novel -- tChapter 5. The Invisible Aristocrat -- tChapter 6. The Physiognomic Fallacy -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this path-breaking study of the intersections between visual and literary culture, Christopher J. Lukasik explores how early Americans grappled with the relationship between appearance and social distinction in the decades between the American Revolution and the Civil War.Through a wide range of evidence, including canonical and obscure novels, newspapers, periodicals, scientific and medical treatises, and plays as well as conduct manuals, portraits, silhouettes, and engravings, Discerning Characters charts the transition from the eighteenth century's emphasis on performance and manners to the search for a more reliable form of corporeal legibility in the wake of the Revolution. The emergence of physiognomy, which sought to understand a person's character based on apparently unchanging facial features, facilitated a larger shift in perception about the meanings of physical appearance and its relationship to social distinction.The ensuing struggle between the face as a pliable medium of cultural performance and as rigid evidence of social standing, Lukasik argues, was at the center of the post-Revolutionary novel, which imagined physiognomic distinction as providing stability during a time of cultural division and political turmoil. As Lukasik shows, this tension between a model of character grounded in the fluid performances of the self and one grounded in the permanent features of the face would continue to shape not only the representation of social distinction within the novel but, more broadly, the practices of literary production and reception in nineteenth-century America across a wide range of media.The result is a new interdisciplinary interpretation of the rise of the novel in America that reconsiders the political and social aims of the genre during the fifty years following the Revolution. In so doing, Discerning Characters powerfully rethinks how we have read—and continue to read—both novels and each other.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aLiterature and societyzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aPhysiognomyzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aSocial perceptionzUnited StatesxHistory. 4aLiterature. 7aHISTORY / United States / Revolutionary Period (1775-1800).2bisacsh  aAmerican History.  aAmerican Studies.  aCultural Studies.  aLiterature.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package American Historyz978311041349608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Pac